    <section class="faq-section" style="margin-top: 4rem;">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <details>
            <summary>What is a high dividend ETF?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">A high dividend ETF is a fund that invests in a basket of stocks known for paying above-average dividend yields relative to the broader market, providing investors with regular income streams.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>Are high dividend ETFs safe?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">While generally less volatile than high-growth stocks, they carry risks. The underlying stocks can lose value, and extremely high yields can sometimes indicate financial distress (yield traps). Diversification within the ETF mitigates some risk.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>How are ETF dividends taxed?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">ETF dividends are typically taxed as either qualified or ordinary dividends, depending on how long you have held the ETF and the nature of the underlying corporate distributions. Consult a tax professional for specific advice.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>Is it better to invest in dividend ETFs or individual dividend stocks?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">Dividend ETFs offer instant diversification and lower idiosyncratic risk, making them ideal for passive investors. Individual stocks require more research but offer the potential to target higher yields or specific companies.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>Do high dividend ETFs provide capital appreciation?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">Yes, but typically less than growth-oriented ETFs. Their primary focus is income generation, but the underlying stocks can appreciate over time, contributing to total return.</p>
        </details>

    </section>
